    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "14a932f7_a5d742b6",
        "filename": "src/codec/SkWuffsCodec.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 343,
      "author": {
        "id": 8223
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-11-07T01:38:31Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I don\u0027t fully understand the get_scaled_dimension implementation (and how I should re-implement it in Wuffs). It says:\n\n```\nstatic inline int get_scaled_dimension(int srcDimension, int sampleSize) {\n    if (sampleSize \u003e srcDimension) {\n        return 1;\n    }\n    return srcDimension / sampleSize;\n}\n```\n\nSo, if sampleSize is 16 and the original height (srcDimension) is 5, then it will return 1. But elsewhere, SkSampler::rowNeeded is:\n\n```\nbool rowNeeded(int row) const {\n    return (row - get_start_coord(fSampleY)) % fSampleY \u003d\u003d 0;\n}\n```\n\nand get_start_coord is:\n\n```\nstatic inline int get_start_coord(int sampleFactor) { return sampleFactor / 2; };\n```\n\nSo when sampleSize or sampleFactor is 16, get_start_coord returns 8, but none of the 5 rows (in the range [0..4]) have rowNeeded return true, because only rows 8, 24, 40, 56, etc are needed. This seems inconsistent.\n\nIn another inconsistency, if the (unscaled) image instead had 30 rows, get_scaled_dimension would return 1, but there are two rows for which rowNeeded would return true: row 8 and row 24.\n\nShould get_scaled_dimension instead return 0 in the 5-row case? Does Skia allow empty (0-width and/or 0-height) images? Or should get_start_coord instead return 0 instead of (sampleFactor / 2), so that sampling a non-empty image (including 1-pixel high images) always has at least one participating row (one where rowNeeded returns true)? Furthermore, should get_scaled_dimension round up instead of round down?\n\n```\nstatic inline int get_scaled_dimension(int srcDimension, int sampleSize) {\n    return (srcDimension + sampleSize - 1) / sampleSize;\n}\n```",
      "revId": "8a250dc152e4a93801f77cbcb19c2e490656b67b",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "971e9a3f_04eab5dd",
        "filename": "src/codec/SkWuffsCodec.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 343,
      "author": {
        "id": 5255
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-11-07T18:34:17Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e I don\u0027t fully understand the get_scaled_dimension implementation (and how I should re-implement it in Wuffs). It says:\n\u003e \n\u003e ```\n\u003e static inline int get_scaled_dimension(int srcDimension, int sampleSize) {\n\u003e     if (sampleSize \u003e srcDimension) {\n\u003e         return 1;\n\u003e     }\n\u003e     return srcDimension / sampleSize;\n\u003e }\n\u003e ```\n\u003e \n\u003e So, if sampleSize is 16 and the original height (srcDimension) is 5, then it will return 1. But elsewhere, SkSampler::rowNeeded is:\n\u003e \n\u003e ```\n\u003e bool rowNeeded(int row) const {\n\u003e     return (row - get_start_coord(fSampleY)) % fSampleY \u003d\u003d 0;\n\u003e }\n\u003e ```\n\u003e \n\u003e and get_start_coord is:\n\u003e \n\u003e ```\n\u003e static inline int get_start_coord(int sampleFactor) { return sampleFactor / 2; };\n\u003e ```\n\u003e \n\u003e So when sampleSize or sampleFactor is 16, get_start_coord returns 8, but none of the 5 rows (in the range [0..4]) have rowNeeded return true, because only rows 8, 24, 40, 56, etc are needed. This seems inconsistent.\n\nThis is a case where we didn\u0027t do a good job making it obvious to someone unfamiliar with the code what\u0027s going on. (And I\u0027m open to CLs that provide improvements in clarity or fixes/ refactors/new ideas!) If the input sampleSize is 16 and the dimension is 5, we end up with a scaled_dimension of 1. But we also internally recompute the sampleSize that we\u0027ll use for rowNeeded and get_start_coord (https://skia.googlesource.com/skia/+/9803e0c522ed69c9204fcfc4893ab1d63266836b/src/codec/SkSampledCodec.cpp#204). In this case (assuming no subset and the GIF image fills the canvas), the sampleFactor we use would be 5. So the start_coord would be 2, and rowNeeded(2) will return true. 4 *also* returns true, but we separately check against the destination height so that we do not use row 4 (https://skia.googlesource.com/skia/+/9803e0c522ed69c9204fcfc4893ab1d63266836b/src/codec/SkGifCodec.cpp#445).\n\n\u003e \n\u003e In another inconsistency, if the (unscaled) image instead had 30 rows, get_scaled_dimension would return 1, but there are two rows for which rowNeeded would return true: row 8 and row 24.\n\nAgain, we rely on the separate check to ensure that we only use one of those rows.\n\n\u003e \n\u003e Should get_scaled_dimension instead return 0 in the 5-row case? Does Skia allow empty (0-width and/or 0-height) images? \n\nNo, Skia generally doesn\u0027t allow empty images. See skbug.com/3534 and https://codereview.chromium.org/830033003. SkBitmap technically allows zero-width and zero-height. I don\u0027t know whether anyone takes advantage of that, but the intent is for the decoder to never create an empty image.\n\n\u003e Or should get_start_coord instead return 0 instead of (sampleFactor / 2), so that sampling a non-empty image (including 1-pixel high images) always has at least one participating row (one where rowNeeded returns true)? Furthermore, should get_scaled_dimension round up instead of round down?\n\u003e \n\u003e ```\n\u003e static inline int get_scaled_dimension(int srcDimension, int sampleSize) {\n\u003e     return (srcDimension + sampleSize - 1) / sampleSize;\n\u003e }\n\u003e ```\n\nI think the adjusted sampleSize should ensure that we have at least one participating row. As for the direction to round, I don\u0027t have a strong preference, but this is the direction we\u0027ve always rounded. FWIW, in b/27118688 we discussed lining up the rounding, which changes depending on whether we\u0027re relying completely on libjpeg(-turbo) or doing our own calculation.\n\nAs for returning 0 - we could just drop get_start_coord and always start with 0. But then we\u0027d end up with a result that is sampled from the upper left corner. (Maybe that would be okay, but the intent was to get a sampling from roughly the center of the image. OTOH, starting with 0 might help with the seams we sometimes see when decoding multiple sampled subsets of the same image.)",
      "parentUuid": "14a932f7_a5d742b6",
      "revId": "8a250dc152e4a93801f77cbcb19c2e490656b67b",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
